Part 2: Interpolation Basics

2.1 Defining Interpolation and Scenarios

Interpolation is defined as “predicting values for cells in a raster from a limited number of sample data points”[1].

You could use interpolation to create a prediction for rainfall across the State of California, using data collected in rain gauges at each UC Campus (one campus rain gauge = 1 sample data point). California’s Air Resources Control Board can monitor air quality and make assessments using air quality data collected throughout the state along highway corridors.

What other types of data could you interpolate?

Part 3: Interpolating Elevation Surfaces: Triangular Irregular Networks (TINs)

From QGIS: TIN interpolation uses sample points to create a surface formed by triangles based on nearest neighbour point information. [x]

  1. Begin by changing your symbology to represent elevation in feet based off the corresponding column (Elev_Gnd_F). This is a vector layer of points - spread out points do not give us a strong visual for a mountainous surface.

  2. In the Geoprocessing pane, search for Create TIN

  3. Name your output OregonTIN

  4. Set your coordinate system to match that of the Climate data

        Input Features: Climate

        Constrained Delauney: leave unchecked

  6. Run!

Part 4. Decision Making with Interpolation


4.1 Order of Operations: When we interpolate data, we must work through an order of operations.

Visual Summary courtesy of Esri


4.2 Key Assumptions: Just like with statistics (that’s what interpolation is behind the scenes!), we have to explore our data ahead of time to get a better understanding of it to make analysis decisions. There are several key assumptions to verify through Exploratory Spatial Data Analysis (ESDA)

   a. Are the data representative of a Continuous surface? Is there a value everywhere in the surface? Think about rainfall over an area. Even if it’s NOT raining, a 0 measurement is still a value. Temperature is also helpful to think about. There isn’t ever NOT temperature.

   b. Is there Spatial Autocorrelation? With spatial autocorrelation, things that are closer together are more closely related (Waldo Tobler’s First Law of Geography!)

   c. Is there Stationarity? For any two points, their consistent distance from eachother is most important. Specific (x,y,z) location doesn’t matter. Distance explains correlation.

   d. Does the data have Normal Distribution? Data, if plotted in a chart, should have a nice bell-curve shape, with 95% of data falling within the first two standard deviations.

   e. Is there No Spatial Clustering? Data should be randomly or regularly spaced over the surface.

   f. Are there Global Trends? A fixed, non-random (deterministic) trend in the data explains large scale variation in your phenomenon- like how elevation may influence temperature. That relationship occurs globally.

4.3 Create a Prediction Surface This middle step of the full process is where you create your interpolated data. In part 5 below, you will explore data to better understand some key assumptions.

4.4 Cross Validate After running your interpolation, it is critical to cross-validate your results! Were your predicted values comparable to the measured values (aka “sanity check”). We’ll do this in Part 6. You can also run other interpolation methods to see if you get similar results.

Part 6. Interpolation Methods

How to Choose a Method of Interpolation

Phenomena can be measured in various ways depending on your analysis goal.

The data type of a measured phenomenon determines which geostatistical interpolation methods apply to the analysis. However, the cross-validation metrics and graphs should be evaluated to ensure that the prediction surface is valid.

   2D Surfaces: x coordinate, y coordinate, value for thing being measured

   3D Surfaces: x coordinate, y coordinate, z coordinate (aka elevation)
   and value for thing being measured

   Polygon Surfaces: reaggregate (up or downscale) polygons to fill in missing data

Now that we know what three datatypes we can interpolate with, we can look at different types of interpolating to do for each datatype.

Is our climate data 2D, 3D, or Polygon? When we looked at the attribute table, we can see there is an Elev_Gnd_F (ground elevation in feet) and Elev_Gnd_m (ground elevation in meters).

Submit a screenshot showing the spatial reference for the Climate layer and highlight/circle the units.

Part 7. Interpolating Practice: Kriging

Pronounced Kreeeging…

Kriging looks at points within a specific distance range to calculate missing values. It is a geostatistical approach to interpolation, also called a stochastic method. [2]

Search for the Geoprocessing tool Empirical Bayesian Kriging and open it.
a. Set your input features to Climate (your data layer)

b. Set your Z value field to Mean Aug Temp

c. Wait, isn’t Z normally representative of elevation? Hover over the blue info icon and read the description. It says…” Field that holds a height or magnitude value for each point… we’re analyzing August Mean Temp, not elevation, so that’s why we’re inputting Mean August Temperatures.

d. Name your output raster ClimateKriging

e. Accept all other defaults.

Click the dropdown for Output Parameters: See that we are creating a prediction surface? Remember that was the middle of 3 steps within the interpolation workflow.

f. Run the Tool.

Part 8. Interpolating Practice: Inverse Distance Weighting (IDW)

With Inverse Distance Weighting, the “strength” of influence one point has on another decreases the farther away it is. Unlike Kriging, IDW looks at ALL the points and assigns weights. It is a deterministic method of interpolation [3]

From QGIS: “In the IDW interpolation method, the sample points are weighted during interpolation such that the influence of one point relative to another declines with distance from the unknown point you want to create.”

Inverse Distance Weighting

In your ArcGIS Pro project…

  1. Access the IDW (Geostatistical Analyst Tool) geoprocessing tool
  2. Set your input features to Climate (your data layer)
  3. Set your Z value field to Mean Aug Temp
  4. Name your Output geostatistical laer ClimateIDW
  5. Accept the remaining defaults and Run
